Food Hub Data Analysis Project¶

Code by Juan D. Correa (Oba Ozai) - Dec 2024¶

Context¶

The number of restaurants in New York is increasing day by day. Lots of students and busy professionals rely on those restaurants due to their hectic lifestyles. Online food delivery service is a great option for them. It provides them with good food from their favorite restaurants. A food aggregator company FoodHub offers access to multiple restaurants through a single smartphone app.

The app allows the restaurants to receive a direct online order from a customer. The app assigns a delivery person from the company to pick up the order after it is confirmed by the restaurant. The delivery person then uses the map to reach the restaurant and waits for the food package. Once the food package is handed over to the delivery person, he/she confirms the pick-up in the app and travels to the customer's location to deliver the food. The delivery person confirms the drop-off in the app after delivering the food package to the customer. The customer can rate the order in the app. The food aggregator earns money by collecting a fixed margin of the delivery order from the restaurants.

Objective¶

The food aggregator company has stored the data of the different orders made by the registered customers in their online portal. They want to analyze the data to get a fair idea about the demand of different restaurants which will help them in enhancing their customer experience. Suppose you are hired as a Data Scientist in this company and the Data Science team has shared some of the key questions that need to be answered. Perform the data analysis to find answers to these questions that will help the company to improve the business.

Data Description¶

The data contains the different data related to a food order. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • order_id: Unique ID of the order
  • customer_id: ID of the customer who ordered the food
  • restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant
  • cuisine_type: Cuisine ordered by the customer
  • cost: Cost of the order
  • day_of_the_week: Indicates whether the order is placed on a weekday or weekend (The weekday is from Monday to Friday and the weekend is Saturday and Sunday)
  • rating: Rating given by the customer out of 5
  • food_preparation_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the restaurant to prepare the food. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the restaurant's order confirmation and the delivery person's pick-up confirmation.
  • delivery_time: Time (in minutes) taken by the delivery person to deliver the food package. This is calculated by taking the difference between the timestamps of the delivery person's pick-up confirmation and drop-off information

Initial Observations:¶

The DataFrame has 9 columns as mentioned in the Data Dictionary. Data in each row corresponds to the order placed by a customer.

The dataset has 1,898 entries and 9 columns. Here's a summary of potential issues observed in the data:

Dataset Overview: Columns: order_id: Unique ID for each order. customer_id: Unique customer identifier. restaurant_name: Name of the restaurant. cuisine_type: Type of cuisine ordered. cost_of_the_order: Cost of the order (numeric). day_of_the_week: Indicates weekday or weekend. rating: Customer rating for the order. Contains the value "Not given." food_preparation_time: Time taken to prepare the food (numeric). delivery_time: Time taken to deliver the food (numeric). Observed Issues: rating column: Contains the value "Not given," which is non-numeric and will interfere with numeric calculations or aggregations. Missing or Invalid Values: No explicit null values are reported, but "Not given" in rating should be treated as missing. Potential Data Type Adjustments: rating is stored as an object but should be numeric if cleaned.

Question 5: How many orders are not rated?¶

In [79]:
# Replace 'raiting' with the actual column name if it differs
raiting_column = 'rating'
# Convert the column to numeric, forcing invalid entries to NaN
df[raiting_column] = pd.to_numeric(df[raiting_column], errors='coerce')
# Count valid ratings (non-NaN and within the range 0 to 5)
valid_ratings_count = df[(df[raiting_column] >= 0) & (df[raiting_column] <= 5)].shape[0]
# Count invalid ratings (NaN or outside the range 0 to 5)
invalid_ratings_count = df[~((df[raiting_column] >= 0) & (df[raiting_column] <= 5))].shape[0]

Question 17: What are your conclusions from the analysis? What recommendations would you like to share to help improve the business? (You can use cuisine type and feedback ratings to drive your business recommendations)¶

  1. Popular Cuisine Types:

    • Certain cuisine types, such as American and Japanese, tend to dominate orders, especially on weekends.
    • These cuisines likely appeal to a broader audience and might represent a strategic focus for marketing or promotions.

  2. Ratings and Customer Satisfaction:

    • Restaurants with high ratings (greater than 4) are not uniformly distributed across cuisine types. For instance, Shake Shack and The Meatball Shop stand out as high performers.
    • Restaurants with lower ratings may struggle to retain customers, potentially due to quality or delivery issues.

  3. Delivery Times:

    • The mean delivery time on weekends (22.47 minutes) is significantly faster than on weekdays (28.34 minutes). This might be due to better traffic conditions or higher operational efficiency during weekends.
    • However, a non-negligible percentage of orders (10.54%) take over 60 minutes, which might lead to customer dissatisfaction.

  4. Revenue Insights:

    • The majority of the revenue is driven by higher-value orders (costing over $20). Promotions targeting these customers could boost profits further.
    • A smaller but steady revenue stream comes from mid-range orders ($5$20), highlighting the need for efficient operations to maintain profitability.

    Conclusion: By focusing on popular cuisine types, addressing delivery inefficiencies, and leveraging customer feedback for continuous improvement, the company can enhance customer satisfaction, drive revenue growth, and maintain a competitive edge in the food delivery market.

Recommendations:¶

  1. Focus on High-Performing Cuisine Types:

    • Expand partnerships with restaurants offering popular cuisine types (e.g., American and Japanese). This could involve promotional campaigns or exclusive delivery agreements.

  2. Improve Delivery Times:

    • Optimize weekday operations to bring delivery times closer to weekend levels. This could involve:
      • Route Optimization: Use data analytics to identify faster routes or clusters with high order volumes.
      • Staffing Adjustments: Ensure adequate staffing during peak weekday hours.

  3. Enhance Low-Rating Restaurants:

    • Work closely with restaurants that consistently receive ratings below 4 to address quality issues. Provide detailed feedback or incentives for improvement.
    • Introduce a 'Verified Quality' badge for restaurants that improve ratings or maintain high standards.

  4. Utilize Feedback Ratings:

    • Implement a targeted feedback system to identify specific areas for improvement (e.g., taste, packaging, or temperature of food).
    • Encourage customers to leave detailed reviews, which can guide improvements and boost transparency.

  5. Promotional Campaigns:

    • Offer discounts or loyalty programs for orders over $20, as these customers contribute significantly to revenue.
    • Launch weekend-specific promotions highlighting fast delivery times and popular cuisine types to drive more weekend sales.

  6. Streamline Low-Profit Segments:

    • Evaluate orders in the $5$20 range to identify inefficiencies. Encourage customers to increase order sizes through bundle deals or free delivery for orders above a certain threshold.

  7. Data-Driven Growth:

    • Regularly analyze customer demographics and order patterns to personalize marketing strategies and refine offerings based on demand trends.

Additional Observations about using the median to fill the empty ratings.

How much the rest of the results would have varied the overall results we have?¶

To determine how much the results would vary if you used different methods to fill the empty values, you can compare the results obtained using different imputation methods. Common methods include using the mean, median, mode, or even a constant value. You can calculate the results for each method and compare them to see the variation.###

How can using the median to fill the empty values be justified in this case?¶

Using the median to fill empty values can be justified in several ways:

Robustness to Outliers: The median is less affected by outliers compared to the mean. If your data has outliers, the median can provide a more accurate central tendency.

Skewed Distributions: If the ratings data is skewed, the median can be a better measure of central tendency than the mean. Preserving Distribution: Using the median can help preserve the overall distribution of the data, especially if the missing values are randomly distributed.###

In [102]:
# Sample data
data = {
    'ratings': [4.5, 4.0, np.nan, 3.5, 5.0, np.nan, 4.2, 3.8, np.nan]
}
df = pd.DataFrame(data)

# Imputation methods
mean_imputed = df['ratings'].fillna(df['ratings'].mean())
median_imputed = df['ratings'].fillna(df['ratings'].median())
mode_imputed = df['ratings'].fillna(df['ratings'].mode()[0])
constant_imputed = df['ratings'].fillna(4.0)  # Example constant value

# Compare results
print("Original Data:\n", df)
print("Mean Imputed:\n", mean_imputed)
print("Median Imputed:\n", median_imputed)
print("Mode Imputed:\n", mode_imputed)
print("Constant Imputed:\n", constant_imputed)

# Justification for using median
print("\nJustification for using median:")
print("1. Robustness to Outliers: Median is less affected by outliers.")
print("2. Skewed Distributions: Median is a better measure of central tendency for skewed data.")
print("3. Preserving Distribution: Median helps preserve the overall distribution of the data.")
